You need two pieces: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` and **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on EditProductPage

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with cancel logic and dirty tracking

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task Cancel()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "Discard changes and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");
            if (!discard) return;
        }
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Navigation guard in AppShell (catches swipe-back / hardware back)

The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the custom button tap, but the user can also swipe back or press the Android hardware back button. Guard that in `AppShell`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`GetDeferral()`** is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- **`args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop`** ensures the guard only fires on back-navigation, not forward pushes.
- **`BackButtonBehavior.Command`** replaces the default back-button tap entirely, so your `CancelCommand` handles its own confirmation and calls `GoToAsync("..")` explicitly.
- The `OnNavigating` guard catches swipe-back and hardware back that bypass the custom button.
